In[10]:
# Clean categorical strings
def clean_str(x):
    if pd.isna(x):
        return x
    return x.strip().title()

for col in ['Car_Brand', 'Car_Model', 'Car_Type', 'Showroom_Location', 'Fuel_Type']:
    df[col] = df[col].apply(clean_str)

# For numerical columns
numerical_cols = ['Year', 'Price', 'Units_Sold', 'Customer_Rating']

for col in numerical_cols:
    mean_val = df[col].mean()
    median_val = df[col].median()
    mode_val = df[col].mode().iloc[0]  # mode() returns a Series; take first mode
    print(f"{col}: Mean = {mean_val}, Median = {median_val}, Mode = {mode_val}")

Descriptive Statistics

We calculate mean, median, mode, standard deviation, and variance for numerical and categorical variables. This helps us understand the central tendencies, variability, and the most common categories, which guide further data cleaning and modeling.

Plot distributions of key numerical variables and aggregated sales by year and brand to understand underlying patterns.

In[42]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
sns.histplot(df['Price'].dropna(),kde = True).set(title='Price Distribution')
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2 
sns.histplot(df['Units_Sold'].dropna(),kde = True).set(title='Unit Sold Distribution')
plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
sns.histplot(df['Customer_Rating'].dropna(), kde=True).set(title='Customer Rating Distribution')
Out[42]:
[Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Customer Rating Distribution')]

Distribution Insights

  • Price Distribution:
    The price distribution is right-skewed, with most vehicles priced between 0.5 million and 6 million. There are fewer very high-priced cars, indicating a concentration around mid-range pricing, but luxury/high-end vehicles are also present.

  • Units Sold Distribution:
    The units sold per record fall mostly in the 100500 range. The spread is relatively uniform, indicating that sales are quite well distributed among different cars or showrooms. There is no heavy skew or strong concentration at either end, suggesting a healthy mix of popular and less popular vehicles in the sales records.

  • Customer Rating Distribution:
    Ratings are mainly between 2.5 and 5, with peaks near 3.0 and 4.5. The distribution is slightly bimodal, indicating that while many cars have good customer ratings, a significant portion have average ratings. This could reflect true customer sentiment diversity or varying product/service quality across brands or models.

Summary:

  • There are no extreme anomalies or heavy skews, but price tilts toward mid-to-high values, sales are well dispersed, and customer ratings show both high and moderate satisfaction clusters.
  • These patterns suggest that both economy and premium segments are represented, with opportunities for deeper segmentation analysis.

# Heatmap for correlation matrix of numerical variables: Price, Units_Sold,Customer_Rating, Year
numerical_cols = ['Price', 'Units_Sold', 'Customer_Rating', 'Year']
corr_matrix = df[numerical_cols].corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title('Correlation Heatmap of Numerical Features')
plt.show()
  • No strong linear relationship exists between Price, Units Sold, Customer Rating, or Year.
  • This suggests that more complex or non-linear features (or categorical interactions such as brand, location, fuel type, or car model) may be required to effectively model and explain variations in Units Sold.

Insights from Pair Plot of Key Numerical Variables by Car Brand

  • Sales strongly correlate with Price and Units Sold, as expected.
  • Customer Rating shows little correlation with Price or Sales.
  • Most brands appear consistently across years, indicating balanced data.
  • Price and Sales distributions are right-skewed, with many mid-range values.
  • No clear outliers or unusual clusters observed.
  • Suggest exploring customer ratings further and applying log-transformations for modeling.

# Sales trend over years

plt.title('Total Units Sold by Year')
plt.ylabel('Sales By Year')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.show()

Identifying Outliers

In[78]:

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

Out[78]:
[Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Box Plot for Price')]

Outlier Analysis Insights

Based on the box plots for both Price and Units_Sold, all the data points fall within the whisker ranges, with no individual points represented as outliers beyond the boxplot "fences". This indicates that there are no significant statistical outliers present in these two numerical variables. The distributions appear to be compact without extreme high or low anomalies.
Conclusion:
Since there are no apparent outliers in Price or Units_Sold, we can proceed to the next stages of analysis or modeling without applying further outlier treatment.
